de.dfki.lt.hfc

Class OperatorRegistry

  • java.lang.Object
    • de.dfki.lt.hfc.OperatorRegistry

  • public final class OperatorRegistry
extends java.lang.Object
    OperatorRegistry encapsulates code centered around the dynamic loading of classes encoding operators, and the creation of instances which are unknown at compile time
    Since:
    JDK 1.5
    See Also:
    Operator, FunctionalOperator, RelationalOperator, Object, Class, Constructor

    • Field Summary

      Fields 
      Modifier and Type Field and Description
      static boolean EXIT_WHEN_REGISTRATION_FAILS
      if true, register() exits with error code 1 in case registration fails; if false, register() returns null in case registration fails
      protected java.util.Hashtable<java.lang.String,Operator> nameToFo
      the association between a class name and its _singleton_ instance (an operator)
      static java.lang.String OPERATOR_PATH
      all (custom) operators should be put into package de.dfki.lt.hfc.operators
      private TupleStore tupleStore
      will be set by the unary constructor and is accessible to every instance of a functional or relational operator

        OperatorRegistry(TupleStore tupleStore)

    • Method Summary

      Methods 
      Modifier and Type Method and Description
      protected Operator checkAndRegister(java.lang.String className)
      checks whether there has already been an operator registered for the _fully-qualified_ class name; if so, the operator is returned; if not, a new one is created, stored/registered, and returned
      BindingTable[] evaluate(java.lang.String className, BindingTable[] args)
      evaluate(String className, BindingTable[] args) should only be used for _relational_ operators
      int evaluate(java.lang.String className, int[] args)
      potentially constructs an instance of className by dynamically loading the corresponding class; given that instance, the apply() method of its class is called; evaluate(String className, int[] args) should only be used for _functional_ operators
      BindingTable[] evaluate(java.lang.String className, java.lang.String packageName, BindingTable[] args)
      now something similar for a relational operator
      int evaluate(java.lang.String className, java.lang.String packageName, int[] args)
      this version of evaluate() distinguishes between the class name and the package path
      BindingTable[] evaluateNoCheck(java.lang.String className, BindingTable[] args)
      evaluate(String className, BindingTable[] args) should only be used for _relational_ operators
      int evaluateNoCheck(java.lang.String className, int[] args)
      contrary to evaluate(), this method does NOT check whether the predicate is already registered and directly applies the functional operator to its arguments evaluate(String className, int[] args) should only be used for _functional_ operators
      private Operator register(java.lang.String className)
      generates a new functional operator instance for className, sets its public field tupleStore with this tupleStore, and generates an association between the class name and the specific instance of that class
